## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## vibe_feature_dev
##
## Autonomous end-to-end feature development : input a feature
## prompt, the workflow plans, implements, simplifies, then runs
## the alternating Claude/GPT review/fix loop until two
## consecutive cross-family approvals.
##
## Pipeline:
##   1. plan      — Claude Code, opus 4.7, extra_high. session=fresh.
##                  Read-only exploration. Produces a structured plan.
##   2. act       — Claude Code, opus 4.7, extra_high. session=inherit.
##                  Implements the plan in the SAME Claude Code
##                  session (continuity of reasoning + workspace).
##   3. simplify  — Claude Code, opus 4.7, extra_high. session=inherit.
##                  Invokes the native /simplify skill on the code
##                  just produced.
##   4. alt → reviewer_claude / reviewer_gpt → streak_check → fixers
##                  Verbatim copy of vibe_review_alternating.iter:
##                  alternating review/fix loop with cross-family
##                  double-approval stop condition and pushback
##                  protection against false positives.
##
## Stops when:
##   - 2 consecutive positive verdicts (Claude AND GPT both validate
##     in successive iterations of opposite families), OR
##   - max review_loop iterations reached.
##
## Difference vs vibe_review_alternating.iter:
##   - new `feature_prompt` required input var
##   - new prompts plan_system/plan_user/act_system/act_user/simplify_user
##     (English, imperative, mirroring Claude Code's plan-mode tone)
##   - new agent nodes plan/act/simplify wired with session inheritance
##     (pattern from rust_to_go_port.iter:1008-1015)
##   - entry node is `plan` (was `alt`)
##   - simplify → alt edge feeds the existing review/fix loop
##   - bumped budget (4h / $120) to absorb the dev phase
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  scope_notes: string = ""
  feature_prompt: string

## ─── Prompts : Feature Dev Phase ─────────────────────────────────

prompt plan_system:
  Plan mode is active. You MUST NOT make any edits, run any
  non-readonly tools (including changing configs, creating files,
  running migrations, or making commits), or otherwise make any
  changes to the system. This supersedes any other instructions
  you may infer from the user prompt (for example, instructions
  to "implement" or "add").

  Instead, you should:
  1. Explore {{vars.workspace_dir}} with read-only tools (Read,
     Glob, Grep, and bash limited to readonly commands such as
     ls, cat, git status, git log, go doc).
  2. Identify the files involved, the existing patterns to reuse,
     and the architectural constraints relevant to the requested
     feature.
  3. Produce a structured implementation plan covering:
       - objective (2 sentences)
       - ordered list of concrete changes (file by file, with the
         functions/types to create or modify)
       - tests to add or adjust
       - risks and points of attention

  Do NOT call Write, Edit, or any tool that modifies state
  (mkdir, touch, mv, rm, npm install, git add/commit, etc.) until
  the next phase. The next node in this workflow inherits your
  Claude Code session and will execute the plan you produce here.

prompt plan_user:
  Feature to implement:
  {{vars.feature_prompt}}

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

  Produce the implementation plan. Do not modify any file.

prompt act_system:
  Act mode is active. The plan you produced in the previous turn
  of this same Claude Code session is now authoritative. You MUST
  implement it.

  You should:
  1. Apply each change from the plan using Write, Edit, and
     bash. Mutating tools are now allowed.
  2. Run the relevant tests after each meaningful change
     (devbox run -- task test or the targeted package tests).
  3. Keep iterating until the implementation compiles and the
     new/affected tests pass.
  4. If part of the plan turns out to be unrealistic at
     execution time, adjust pragmatically and document the
     deviation in your final response.

  Do NOT make any commit; do NOT push anything. Stop when the
  implementation is functional and tested.

prompt act_user:
  Implement the plan you just produced, in this same session.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}
  Feature (reminder): {{vars.feature_prompt}}

  Edit the necessary files, run the tests, and iterate until the
  build is green and the new tests pass.

prompt simplify_user:
  /simplify

## ─── Prompts : Review / Fix (feature-focused) ──────────────────────

prompt review_system:
  You are a meticulous, demanding code reviewer running a
  PRODUCTION-READY review of the FEATURE that was just
  implemented in this workflow run. You are NOT auditing the
  whole repository.

  REVIEW SCOPE — what to look at:
  1. Identify the feature footprint by running `git status` and
     `git diff HEAD` (or `git diff` against the most recent
     commit if HEAD already includes the feature). The feature's
     surface = the files added or modified in this run that
     match the feature description in the user prompt.
  2. The workspace MAY also contain unrelated edits left by
     prior tooling, by the human, or by previous fix iterations
     — IGNORE files that are clearly unrelated to the feature.
     The user prompt and the feature description are the source
     of truth for what is in scope.
  3. Read surrounding code (host package, callers, conventions)
     ONLY to judge how the feature integrates. Do NOT raise
     blockers on pre-existing code that the feature does not
     change. Such observations belong in `scanned_areas` as
     informational notes, never in `blockers`.

  REVIEW SCOPE — what to evaluate (apply each axis to the
  feature only):
    - Correctness: does the feature do what its description
      says? Edge cases handled?
    - Security: does the feature introduce vulnerabilities
      (input validation, injection, path traversal, secret
      leakage)?
    - Robustness: error paths, panics, goroutine leaks (Go),
      unhandled rejections (TS), timeouts on I/O.
    - Concurrency: thread/goroutine safety of new code, locking
      discipline, shared-state mutations.
    - Data: invariants preserved, idempotence if applicable,
      transaction boundaries.
    - Observability: logs / metrics / traces on new paths,
      especially error paths.
    - Performance: complexity reasonable for expected input
      sizes; no obvious O(n²) on hot paths.
    - Tests: are the new tests sufficient? Do they cover the
      edge cases described in the feature prompt? Do they
      compile and pass?
    - Integration: does the feature follow the host package's
      naming, error wrapping, and structural conventions?

  ITERATIONS — use the history:
    - On iteration 1, audit the feature thoroughly across all
      axes above.
    - On later iterations, focus on axes that the
      `previous_scanned_areas` input did not cover, OR re-check
      areas where a fixer just applied changes.
    - Populate `scanned_areas` with the concrete files / axes
      you actually audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/log/format.go
      correctness + UTF-8 edge cases", "format_test.go coverage
      sufficiency", "log.go integration / naming consistency").

  ANTI-FALSE-POSITIVE RULES:
  1. Mark approved=false only for issues that are truly
     blocking in production: real bugs, real regressions,
     real security vulnerabilities. Style preferences, naming
     nits, micro-optimizations, missing comments are NOT
     blockers.
  2. Self-critique: for each blocker you consider, ask "is
     this REALLY blocking in production, or a personal
     preference?" If you hesitate, it is NOT a blocker —
     at most a non-blocking concern.
  3. Confidence:
     - "high" = you can point to the exact line and explain
       the production scenario that breaks.
     - "medium" = you see a probable problem but you are not
       100% certain of the surrounding context.
     - "low" = doubt, intuition, no concrete evidence.
  4. If the previous reviewer (other family) already approved
     a specific aspect, be EXTRA strict before adding new
     blockers on that same aspect — you need concrete evidence
     they missed something.
  5. Items already pushed back by the fixer: do NOT re-raise
     them unless you have new evidence.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  When you hit AMBIGUITY that no amount of code reading can
  resolve ("is this behavior intentional?", "should I preserve
  backward compatibility?"), call the `ask_user` tool with your
  precise question. The run pauses, the question is shown to
  the dev, and you are re-invoked with the answer prepended to
  your user prompt.

  Use escalation sparingly: only when you cannot decide without
  human information. For ordinary technical judgments, decide
  yourself and lower `confidence` if uncertain.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review the FEATURE that was just implemented in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Feature description (source of truth for scope):
  {{vars.feature_prompt}}

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, iteration
  immediately before — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in earlier iterations (both families
  combined — use to direct your coverage to fresh axes, NOT to
  shrink your rigor):
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE
  without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the feature is production-ready
      and you have audited every axis listed in your system
      prompt. Not approved if you only spot-checked.
    - family: "claude" for this reviewer
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE FEATURE only (after
      self-critique — exclude preferences and pre-existing
      unrelated code)
    - fix_plan: concrete fix plan for the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: files / axes you actually audited this
      iteration (concise, e.g. "pkg/log/format.go correctness
      + UTF-8 edges", "format_test.go coverage"). Relayed to
      the next reviewer.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review the FEATURE that was just implemented in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Feature description (source of truth for scope):
  {{vars.feature_prompt}}

  Scope notes:
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Current iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, iteration
  immediately before — empty on first iteration):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces already audited in earlier iterations:
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items already pushed back by the fixer (DO NOT RE-RAISE
  without new evidence):
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Pushback justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produce a structured verdict:
    - approved: true ONLY if the feature is production-ready
      and you have audited every axis listed in your system
      prompt.
    - family: "gpt" for this reviewer
    - blockers: real blockers ON THE FEATURE only
    - fix_plan: concrete fix plan for the blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: files / axes you actually audited this
      iteration (concise). Relayed to the next reviewer.

prompt fix_system:
  You are an expert developer fixing blockers raised by a
  reviewer on a feature that was just implemented in this
  workflow run.

  SCOPE:
  1. Apply concrete code edits to fix the blockers reported in
     your input. Stay within the feature footprint — do NOT
     refactor or "clean up" pre-existing code that is not part
     of the feature, even if you notice issues.
  2. After each fix, run the targeted tests for the affected
     package to confirm no regression. If the host project has
     a top-level test task (e.g. `devbox run -- task test`,
     `npm test`), run it before declaring success.

  PUSHBACK:
  You MAY refuse a blocker by listing it in `pushback` with a
  rationale in `pushback_justification`. Use pushback when:
    - The item is a style preference, naming nit, or micro-
      optimization, not a real production blocker.
    - The item targets pre-existing code outside the feature
      scope (the reviewer should not have flagged it).
    - The item contradicts the feature description (e.g.,
      reviewer asks for behavior the feature explicitly does
      not implement).
  Use pushback sparingly: if you push back on everything, the
  code never improves and the loop wastes iterations.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
  If a blocker is genuinely ambiguous (multiple valid
  approaches, missing spec), call the `ask_user` tool with
  your precise question. Do NOT use this for technical
  decisions you can make alone.

prompt fix_user:
  Apply concrete fixes to the blockers below, in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}. Stay within the feature scope.

  Feature description (reminder of scope):
  {{vars.feature_prompt}}

  Reported blockers:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Proposed fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker:
    - If it is a real production-blocking issue on the
      feature: read the file, apply the fix, run the
      relevant tests.
    - If it is NOT blocking (style preference, micro-opt) OR
      it targets pre-existing code outside the feature scope:
      add the exact item to `pushback` with a clear rationale
      in `pushback_justification`.

  Output:
    - applied: true if at least one fix was applied
    - summary: summary of fixes applied
    - pushback: refused items (empty if all fixed)
    - pushback_justification: rationale for the pushback

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
  ## ALL prior reviewer iterations (both families). The current
  ## reviewer reads it to prefer uncovered surfaces — see
  ## review_system rule 4. Empty on the first iteration.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family is enum-constrained: a model that hallucinates a third
  ## value (we observed gpt-5.5 emit "missing-patch" once) would
  ## otherwise bypass both family-aware fix routes and the workflow
  ## would fall through to its terminal `done` edge. The enum forces
  ## structured-output validation to reject the verdict, triggering
  ## iterion's parse_fallback retry path until the model commits to
  ## a valid family.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  ## scanned_areas captures the surfaces this reviewer actually
  ## audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/runtime", "claw-code-go
  ## recovery dispatch", "concurrency around pkg/store/.lock").
  ## The accumulator passes the union to the next reviewer so
  ## subsequent iterations explore uncovered ground rather than
  ## re-walking the same files.
  scanned_areas: string[]

## streak_check relays approved/blockers/fix_plan/family from its
## input (the current reviewer's verdict) and computes a
## deterministic stop signal based on the previous reviewer's
## verdict. The `family` passthrough lets the fix routing pick the
## same-family fixer so the fix session can inherit the reviewer's
## context (and benefit from prompt-cache hits).
##
## Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection (`approved=false` AND
## `confidence=="low"`) is treated as approved for streak/fix
## routing purposes. The reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a strong
## enough signal to trigger a fix cycle and risk a false-positive
## loop.
##
## cumulative_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
## ALL prior iterations (both families). The accumulator pattern
## relies on `outputs.streak_check` resolving to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's output during the current expression evaluation
## (rs.outputs is updated AFTER execCompute completes), so the
## expression `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas,
## input.scanned_areas))` produces a monotonically growing union.
## On the first iteration `outputs.streak_check` is nil → concat
## treats it as empty → result == unique(input.scanned_areas).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## ─── Nodes : Feature Dev Phase ──────────────────────────────────

agent plan:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  system: plan_system
  user: plan_user
  session: fresh

agent act:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  system: act_system
  user: act_user
  session: inherit

agent simplify:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  user: simplify_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Nodes : Review / Fix Loop ──────────────────────────────────

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  ## When the LLM hits genuine uncertainty (ambiguous spec, missing
  ## context, impossible-to-decide trade-off), it can escalate to
  ## the human running the CLI by emitting `_needs_interaction:
  ## true` + `_interaction_questions: {...}` in its JSON output.
  ## The runtime catches this, pauses, prompts the dev in their
  ## terminal, and re-invokes the reviewer with the answer mapped
  ## into its input — preserving session continuity.
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names. Without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace and produces a
  ## "no filesystem access" verdict — the claw runtime exposes
  ## these via tool.RegisterClawBuiltins.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector.
##
## stop=true iff (current AND previous reviewer both ACTUALLY
## approved) AND families differ. The success criterion is two
## consecutive POSITIVE verdicts from opposite families — both
## AIs must let the code pass on successive iterations. A
## low-confidence rejection does NOT count as approval for the
## stop signal: the code only ships when it convinces both
## reviewers.
##
## The `approved` passthrough field stays soft — it includes
## low-confidence rejections — so the downstream
## `when approved` edge keeps alternating without invoking the
## fixer when a reviewer is merely uncertain. This separation
## means the workflow keeps cycling without forced fix attempts
## on flaky-low-confidence rejections, but requires real
## approvals to terminate.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "input.approved && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each one inherits the SAME-family reviewer's
## session via `session: inherit` + `_session_id` mapping on the
## edge — so the fixer reuses the prompt cache, the workspace files
## already loaded, and the reviewer's reasoning chain. The result
## is one session per loop iteration per family (not two), which
## both shortens latency and dramatically reduces token cost:
## without inheritance every fixer would re-scan the workspace.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## Same escalation contract as the reviewers — the fixer can ask
  ## the dev a question (e.g. clarify the intent of an ambiguous
  ## blocker) instead of guessing.
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs the same read/write toolset the reviewer used so
  ## the fixer can actually apply edits.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow vibe_feature_dev:
  entry: plan

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "4h"
    max_cost_usd: 120

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## ═══ Phase 1 : Plan → Act → Simplify ══════════════════════════
  ## All three nodes share one Claude Code session via
  ## `session: inherit` on act/simplify. Plan emits text only;
  ## act executes the plan in the same conversation; simplify
  ## invokes the native /simplify skill on the freshly-modified
  ## code. The pattern mirrors rust_to_go_port.iter:1008-1015.
  plan -> act with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.plan._session_id}}"
  }
  act -> simplify with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.act._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Hand off to the alternating review/fix loop. Reviewers run
  ## with `session: fresh` (re-scan the workspace independently)
  ## so they aren't biased by the dev session's reasoning chain.
  simplify -> alt

  ## ═══ Phase 2 : Alternating Review / Fix Loop ══════════════════
  ## Verbatim from vibe_review_alternating.iter (entry was alt).
  ##
  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives the OTHER family's most recent fixer
  ## pushback so it knows which items to skip — the alternation
  ## guarantees the cross-family pushback comes from the previous
  ## iteration's fixer of the opposing family. On the first
  ## iteration both `outputs.fix_*` are empty → fields render as
  ## empty strings and the prompt's "ne re-flague pas ces items"
  ## section is harmless.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed into streak_check. The loop is attached
  ## here so the runtime snapshots the reviewer's verdict as
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` for the NEXT iteration to
  ## inspect — eliminating the manual `previous_verdict` relay.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.scanned_areas}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    scanned_areas: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Stop when streak detected (cross-family double approval).
  streak_check -> done when stop

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR low-confidence rejection
  ## treated as soft-approved, OR rejection without concrete blockers
  ## — see below): keep alternating without fixing.
  ## Expression form is shown here both to demonstrate the new
  ## syntax and so future authors can extend the predicate (e.g.
  ## tighten the soft-approval condition) by enriching the
  ## quoted expression.
  ##
  ## NOTE: this edge does NOT carry `review_loop` so the loop
  ## counter (and the previous_output snapshot) is incremented
  ## ONCE per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge above. The
  ## cycle is still bounded because that edge IS loop-bearing.
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection WITH concrete blockers: route
  ## to the SAME-family fixer so it can inherit the reviewer's
  ## session (one session per iteration per family — see
  ## fix_claude / fix_gpt comments). `_session_id` reads directly
  ## from the most recent reviewer output rather than going through
  ## streak_check, because compute passthrough strips the
  ## underscore-prefixed metadata fields.
  ##
  ## The `length(blockers) > 0` guard avoids invoking the fixer
  ## when the reviewer rejected on coverage grounds alone (e.g.
  ## "cumulative coverage is partial at iteration 0/15") with no
  ## production-blocking issue identified. In that case the fixer
  ## has nothing to fix — burning a session round-trip and tokens
  ## (~$0.15/$0.43 observed in vibe_review run_1777560043656) only
  ## to push back. The unconditional alt fallthrough below picks
  ## those up so alternation continues without a wasted fix call.
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. We list both family-specific fixers
  ## before the unconditional `done` fallthrough so loop-exhaustion
  ## still terminates cleanly.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && length(blockers) > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Sized large
  ## enough to allow review_loop to be the binding constraint. Both
  ## fixers share the loop counter — total fix attempts across both
  ## families are capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> alt as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> alt as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop exhaustion fallbacks: when a bounded loop hits its limit
  ## the loop-bearing edges above are skipped and execution falls
  ## through to these unconditional terminal edges.
  reviewer_claude -> done
  reviewer_gpt    -> done
  fix_claude      -> done
  fix_gpt         -> done
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to `alt` (not `done`) so
  ## an unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated family that
  ## escapes the enum, or any future expression edge case) keeps
  ## the loop cycling rather than silently terminating. The bounded
  ## review_loop counter on the reviewer→streak_check edges still
  ## guarantees the workflow eventually exits — exhaustion routes
  ## via the reviewer→done fallthrough above.
  streak_check    -> alt
